{"title": "Epistulae Morales Selectae", "description": "Seneca is an important repository of Stoic doctrine. His reputation, based on the ancient testimony, has remained ambiguous down to the present day: he was a Stoic hero who attempted to advise Nero, he was a dissolute hypocrite, he was a Christian saint. That said, his letters provided a format for philosophical discourse that long remained valid for Western Europe. His musings always sprang from concrete situations: the games in the Coliseum, the noise from a public bath below his apartment. Montaigne admired the style of his Latin, which he called \"nerveux\": taut and full of energy. (Summary by Malone)", "duration": 20516, "language": "Latin", "authors": [{"id": "257", "name": "Lucius Annaeus Seneca"}], "coverArt": "https://archive.org/download/LibrivoxCdCoverArt32/Epistulae_Morales_Selectae_1308.jpg", "copyright_year": "1890", "genres": ["Classics (Greek & Latin Antiquity)", "Ancient"], "supporters": [{"role": "Read by", "name": "Malone"}, {"role": "Book Coordinator", "name": "Malone"}, {"role": "Meta Coordinator", "name": "Leni"}, {"role": "Proof Listener", "name": "Kajo"}], "sections": [{"section": 1, "title": "01 - Epistulae 1, 2, 6, 7", "readers": [7601], "path": "https://www.archive.org/download/epistulaemorales_1306/epistulae_01_seneca_64kb.mp3", "duration": 1396}, {"section": 2, "title": "02 - Epistulae 8, 9, 10", "readers": [7601], "path": "https://www.archive.org/download/epistulaemorales_1306/epistulae_02_seneca_64kb.mp3", "duration": 1710}, {"section": 3, "title": "03 - Epistulae 15, 16, 26, 27", "readers": [7601], "path": "https://www.archive.org/download/epistulaemorales_1306/epistulae_03_seneca_64kb.mp3", "duration": 1810}, {"section": 4, "title": "04 - Epistulae 28, 31, 37, 38, 40", "readers": [7601], "path": "https://www.archive.org/download/epistulaemorales_1306/epistulae_04_seneca_64kb.mp3", "duration": 1884}, {"section": 5, "title": "05 - Epistulae 41, 44, 47", "readers": [7601], "path":